==English==

===Etymology===
From French ''[[hélicoptère]]'', from [[Greek]] [[ελικόπτερον]] {{italbrac|helikopteron}}, from [[Ancient Greek]] [[έλιξ]] (genitive [[έλικος]]) {{italbrac|helix}}, {{italbrac|helikos}} “urning, revolving, rotating, spinning” + [[πτερόν]] {{italbrac|pteron}} “wing” or “anything winged”.

===Pronunciation===
*[[w:IPA|IPA]] (UK): /ˈheliˌkɒptə(r)/
*[[w:IPA|IPA]] (US): /ˈhɛliˌkɔptəɻ/
*[[w:IPA|IPA]] (Australia): /ˈheliˌkoptə(r)/
*[[w:SAMPA|SAMPA]] (Australia): /"heli%kopt@(r)/

===Noun===
'''helicopter'''

#An aircraft that is borne along by one or more sets of long rotating blades which allow it to hover, move or land and having a smaller set of blades on its tail that stabilize the aircraft.
#:''We flew over the city in a '''helicopter'''''.
# a powered [[trowel]]ling machine with spinning blades used to spread [[concrete]].

